        <name>16.2.5.3 Convergence with a parameter</name>
        <questiontext>&lt;p class="HELM_exercise"&gt;Exercise&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;For what values of \(x\) are the following series absolutely convergent?&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ol class="HELM_parts"&gt;
    &lt;li&gt;\(\displaystyle{\sum_{p=1}^\infty \frac{(-1)^p x^p}{p}}\) is convergent for all \(|x|\) [[input:ans1]] [[validation:ans1]]&amp;nbsp;[[input:ans2]].&amp;nbsp;[[validation:ans2]]
        &lt;p&gt;[[feedback:prt1]] [[feedback:prt2]]&lt;/p&gt;
    &lt;/li&gt;
    &lt;li&gt;\(\displaystyle{\sum_{p=1}^\infty \frac{(-1)^p x^p}{p!}}\) is convergent for all \(|x|\) [[input:ans3]] [[validation:ans3]] [[input:ans4]].&amp;nbsp;[[validation:ans4]]
        &lt;p&gt;[[feedback:prt3]] [[feedback:prt4]]&lt;/p&gt;
    &lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Hint:&lt;/strong&gt; if the series is absolutely convergent for all values of \(x\), select = and then enter R or all (to signify the real numbers).&lt;/p&gt;</questiontext>
        <questiontextformat>1</questiontextformat>
        <generalfeedback>&lt;ol class="HELM_parts"&gt;
    &lt;li&gt;
        &lt;p&gt;The general term of the related series of positive terms is \(\displaystyle a_p = \frac{|x|^p}{p}\). For this series, using the ratio test we find&lt;/p&gt;
        \[\begin{aligned} \lambda = \lim_{p \to \infty} \frac{a_{p+1}}{a_p} &amp;amp;= \lim_{p \to \infty} \frac{|x|^{p+1}}{p+1} \cdot \frac{p}{|x|^p} \\ &amp;amp;= \lim_{p \to \infty} \frac{p}{p+1} \cdot |x| \\ &amp;amp;= |x|. \end{aligned}\]
        &lt;p&gt;Hence, the original series is absolutely convergent for all \(|x| &amp;lt; 1\). Note that if \(|x| = 1\), then the series of positive terms is the harmonic series, which diverges. Therefore, our series is absolutely convergent if and only if \(|x|
            &amp;lt; 1\).&lt;/p&gt;
    &lt;/li&gt;
    &lt;li&gt;
        &lt;p&gt;The general term of the related series of positive terms is \(\displaystyle a_p = \frac{|x|^p}{p!}\). For this series, using the ratio test we find&lt;/p&gt;
        \[\begin{aligned} \lambda = \lim_{p \to \infty} \frac{a_{p+1}}{a_p} &amp;amp;= \lim_{p \to \infty} \frac{|x|^{p+1}}{(p+1)!} \cdot \frac{p!}{|x|^p} \\ &amp;amp;= \lim_{p \to \infty} \frac{p!}{(p+1)!} \cdot |x| \\ &amp;amp;= \lim_{p \to \infty} \frac{1}{p+1} \cdot
        |x| \\ &amp;amp;= 0 \cdot |x| = 0. \end{aligned}\]
        &lt;p&gt;We have found that \(\lambda = 0 &amp;lt; 1\) irrespective of the value of \(|x|\). Hence, our series is absolutely convergent for all \(|x|\) in \(\mathbb{R}\).&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;</generalfeedback>
